	6. Fair Value Measurements




	ASC 820,

	Fair Value Measurements and Disclosures

	 (ASC 820) defines fair value as the price that
	would be received upon sale of an asset or paid upon transfer of a liability in an orderly transaction between market participants at the measurement date and in the principal or most advantageous market for that asset or liability. The fair value
	should be calculated based on assumptions that market participants would use in pricing the asset or liability, not on assumptions specific to the entity. In addition, the fair value of liabilities should include consideration of non-performance
	risk, including the Companys own credit risk.


	ASC 820 establishes a three-level hierarchy of fair value measurements based on
	whether the inputs to those measurements are observable or unobservable. Observable inputs reflect market data obtained from independent sources, while unobservable inputs reflect the Companys market assumptions. The fair-value hierarchy
	requires the use of observable market data when available and consists of the following levels:


	 




	 


	


	 


	Level 1Quoted prices for identical instruments in active markets;




	 




	 


	


	 


	Level 2Quoted prices for similar instruments in active markets; quoted prices for identical or similar instruments in markets that are not active; and model-derived valuations in which all significant inputs are
	observable in active markets; and




	 




	 


	


	 


	Level 3Valuations derived from valuation techniques in which one or more significant inputs are unobservable.




	 


	F-22






